english:
  title: 'Eight Poems on Eight Ink Paintings: A Gift to Governor Kim'
  author: Kang Hee-meng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A painted duck drifts gracefully on the stone crossing,
    its colored plumage gleaming like silk on the autumn river.
    Beneath the shadow of towering pines, no one watches—
    flying back and forth, it fashions its own pair.

    It cries out and sleeps and feeds, seeming to desire nothing,
    and when the sun falls and the river empties, finds perfect freedom.
    Who knows the heart of this humble observer?
    For ten years I wandered with the autumn of Mirror Lake.

    On Luofu's peak the moon descends into endless dreaming,
    its reflection dipped into the head of West Lake's waters.
    A thousand years of jade-like essence calls in vain—
    I take up the brush to seek what is clear and profound.

    Purple vines coil through emptiness, their brocaded leaves thicken,
    and fragrant whiskers, fine and delicate, tangle together.
    Clearly last night the Dragon King shifted his dwelling—
    he scattered pearls across the wind and rain of autumn.

    The autumn air cuts sharp through deep ravines,
    grape vines stretch their tendrils to light shadow.
    Frost-dried black seeds taste as sweet as honey,
    and I watch the troops of monkeys come seeking, content.

    The dark orchid's radiant leaves are truly beautiful,
    accompanied by autumn wind through thorned branches.
    Together they achieve creation, sharing rain and dew alike—
    now I know Heaven and Earth are moved by no selfish heart.

    I rush through the dust of the world until my hair grows white,
    twice I have watched the bamboo in times of snow and frost.
    In my old age and leisure, I cannot restrain lingering thoughts—
    let me then assume the posture of spring thunder breaking winter's sleep.

    A thousand stalks of noble bamboo embrace a single village,
    the wind strikes them in tumult, the sound troubles the ear.
    In such moments, one need not seek to transmit the spirit—
    yet in distant capitals, such things will be forever missed.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Mirror Lake (鑑湖): A famous lake near Shaoxing in Zhejiang province, associated with natural beauty and seclusion.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Luofu (羅浮): Luofu Mountain, a legendary sacred mountain in Guangdong, known in Chinese literature as a place of immortals and mysticism.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'West Lake (西湖): The celebrated lake near Hangzhou, another symbol of natural beauty and artistic inspiration in Chinese culture.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Dragon King (龍公): A reference to the mythological dragon deity associated with water and precious gems.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Jade-like essence (玉魂): Suggests the eternal, incorruptible spirit of nature.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Spring thunder breaking winter''s sleep: A metaphor for awakening from dormancy, renewal, and the restoration of vital energy.'
